    <string name="tutorial_part_1a">
        You can use the Doomsday algorithm to mentally calculate the day of the week for a given date.\n\n
        The first step is to memorise the Doomsday for each month:
    </string>
    <string name="doomsday_list">A list of Doomsdays</string>
    <string name="tutorial_part_1b">Next, assign each weekday a numerical value:</string>
    <string name="tutorial_part_1c">
        Sunday: 0, Monday: 1\n\n
        Tuesday: 2, Wednesday: 3\n\n
        Thursday: 4, Friday: 5\n\n
        Saturday: 6
    </string>
    <string name="tutorial_part_2a">Anchor days also need to be memorised:</string>
    <string name="anchordays_list">A list of anchor days</string>
    <string name="tutorial_part_2b">With the previous information in mind, you can now calculate the day of the week using the following formula: (mod = remainder of division)</string>
    <string name="tutorial_part_2c">
        (Mod = remainder of division)\n\n
        One final tip, memorise the following multiples:\n\n
        Multiples of 7:\n7, 14, 21, 28\n\n
        Multiples of 12:\n12, 24, 36, 48,\n60, 72, 84, 96
    </string>
    <string name="tutorial_part_3a">Here, the date 3/2/1990 is used as an example:</string>
    <string name="doomsday_example">An example of the Doomsday algorithm in use</string>
    <string name="tutorial_part_3b">
        The anchor day for 1990 is 3, which is Wednesday and the closest Doomsday to 3/2/1990 is 28/2. Next, the number of days between the Doomsday and our given date is 25.\n\n
        25 divided by 7 gives a quotient of 3, meaning there is 3 weeks (21 days) between the Doomsday and the given date.\n\n
        25 - 21 = 4, so going 4 days back from Wednesday (the Doomsday) gives Saturday.\n\n
        This means that 3/2/1990 occurred on a Saturday
    </string>
